{
    "name": "Rebel Risk?",
    "text": "Throughout history, rulers have repeatedly discovered that starving, overtaxed, oppressed, or neglected subjects occasionally object to their circumstances. This objection is typically expressed through riots, revolts, and the sudden appearance of armed peasants outside the city walls.The higher your [Rebel Risk], the greater the chance rebel armies will emerge. Watch for the [REBEL IMMINENT] warning in your turn notifications. Contrary to popular belief, rebels rarely spawn because they enjoy exercise.",
    "presentation": "Alert",
    "choices": [
        {
            "text": "I SHALL CRUSH DA PEASANTS!",
            "uniques": [
                "Comment [Mechanic explanations can be found in Civilopedia -> Resources -> Rebel Risk.]",
                "Triggers a [A Matter of Administration] event <hidden from users> <for [Human player] Civilizations>",
                "Only available <when below [1] [Administrative Briefing]> <hidden from users>"
            ]
        }
    ],
    "civilopediaText": [
        {
            "text": "Review the Civilopedia -> Resources -> Rebel Risk",
            "link": "Resources/Rebel Risk"
        }
    ]
},
{
    "name": "The Plague?",
    "text": "For most of human history, disease has killed more people than wars, famines, and ambitious politicians combined. Cities with poor sanitation become breeding grounds for outbreaks, and once a plague begins spreading, it tends to ignore borders, social class, and optimistic government reports.Maintain high [Sanitation] to reduce the risk of outbreaks. Watch for plague warnings in your notifications. Remember: washing your hands is considerably cheaper than burying half the empire.",
    "presentation": "Alert",
    "choices": [
        {
            "text": "BUILD MORE BATHS!",
            "uniques": [
